    "summary": "The Edict of Milan (313 AD) was an agreement between the emperors Constantine and Licinius that established religious toleration throughout the Roman Empire — granting Christians and all other religions the freedom to practice without persecution and ordering the return of confiscated church property. It was not technically an 'edict' in the formal sense but a letter to provincial governors implementing the agreed policy; the earlier Edict of Toleration (311 AD) by Galerius had already ended official persecution.\n\nThe Edict's significance was transformational: after three centuries of intermittent persecution culminating in Diocletian's [[event:2822|Great Persecution Diocletian]] (303–311 AD), the church emerged from illegality to legal recognition, property rights, and eventually active imperial patronage. The return of confiscated property was a substantial material benefit, and the recognition of Sunday as a public holiday (321 AD) embedded Christianity in the civil calendar. The Edict of Milan has been cited as a foundational document for the concept of religious freedom, though its authors' intent was pragmatic rather than principled: Constantine sought to unify the empire through religious peace, not to establish an abstract right. It marked the beginning of the alliance between church and Roman state that shaped both institutions for centuries.",
